em and their opponents increases; Russians are loath to sue friends and neighbors, but are less reluctant when it comes to strangers or acquaintances. Hendley concludes that the "rule of law" rubric is ill suited to Russia and other authoritarian polities where law matters most—but not all—of the time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCourtszRussia (Federation). 0aLawzRussia (Federation). 4aHistory. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History.  acontemporary Russia, Russian law, conflict resolution, Russian courts, Russia's new justice, judicial independence, justice law.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170810740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501708107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501708107/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles